# Collaboration model

Andrew is the **arbiter of taste and vision**: pleasing, usable, delightful UX. He is not expected to know how the codebase, browser layout, or animation systems work.

The agent is the **implementation expert**. Own the technical consequences of every approach.

## Before building from a user idea

When Andrew describes a behaviour or mechanism in plain language (e.g. “scale text as words disappear so height doesn’t jump”):

1. **Translate** what he wants into the underlying constraint (e.g. “slider Y must stay fixed; headline must not push chrome”).
2. **Name 1–2 simpler alternatives** and one likely failure mode for his idea.
3. **Say which you recommend and why** — don’t silently implement the first interpretation.
4. **Implement the smallest test** when trade-offs are unclear (debug overlay, keyframe table, one phase only).

Challenge early. A short “that approach will probably cause X; consider Y instead” is better than a long fix cycle.

## Red flags — pause and discuss

- Two systems controlling the same property (e.g. line-budget + surge both driving font-size).
- Discrete events (fragment fade) coupled to continuous animation (slider %) without a keyframe plan.
- Layout experiments stacked on unparked milestones without a rollback path.
- “Feels right” specs with no measurable acceptance criteria (font px, Y position, phase name at u=0.52).

## What to deliver back

- Plain-language summary of what changed and why.
- When stuck: propose a **keyframe table** or tune UI instead of tuning magic numbers in chat.
- Park what works; experiment in isolation (see `journey-clarity.mdc`).

Andrew’s screenshots, debug readouts, and “at 52% it goes haywire” are high-quality input — keep asking for those.
